'''Ipmil''' or '''Ipmilbalolaš''' means [[God]] in [[Northern Sami language|Northern Sámi]]. Ipmil has been used by [[Sami people|Sámi]] [[Christian]]s for God. The Creator and ruler of the universe. There are Sámi Christians who believe in [[Laestadianism]] that use Ipmil for God. Ipmil can also be used when translating God from other cultures. Names of God: [[Allah]] ([[Islam]]), [[Adonai]] ([[Judaism]]) could be translated as Ipmil in Northern Sámi. Svenska kyrkan ([[Church of Sweden]]) has a prayer in Northern Sámi with ''Ipmil''.<ref>[http://svenskakyrkan.se/be/prayer/59753 Mon ohcan veahki birget daid  - Svenska kyrkan]</ref> ''Ipmil atte'' means God grant and is a reply to ''buorre beaivi'' (good day). [[Christians]] who believe in the ''[[Trinity]]'' say: ''Áhči'' ([[God the Father|Father]]) and ''Bártni'' ([[God the Son|Son]], [[Jesus Christ]]) and ''Bassi Vuoiŋŋa'' (the [[Holy Spirit (Christianity)|Holy Spirit]]) is ''Ipmil''. The Sámi thought there were three [[deities]]: ''[[Radien-Áhči]]'' (Father), Radien-Bártni (Jesus) and [[Akka (spirit)|Mátterahkka]] (Grandmother Spirit Mátterahkka). In [[Sami mythology]], Mátterahkka is said to have created the body of the children who were placed into the wombs. Ipmil could also have been a name to include all good deities.{{cn|date=November 2016}}

